      <h1>Hitch Weight Distribution & Load Balance Matter </h1>
      <div><div id="news-article">
    
      <p class="postmetadata">
        
          Filed under:
          
            <a href="http://www.hitchinfo.com/index.cfm?event=news.category&amp;categoryName=practical&#32;towing&#32;info" rel="category tag">Practical Towing Info</a> 
          <br />
        
          Tags:
          
            <a href="index.cfm%3Fevent=news.tag&amp;tagName=weight.html" rel="tag">weight</a>, 
            <a href="http://www.hitchinfo.com/index.cfm?event=news.tag&amp;tagName=load&#32;balance" rel="tag">load balance</a>, 
            <a href="http://www.hitchinfo.com/index.cfm?event=news.tag&amp;tagName=trailer&#32;rating" rel="tag">trailer rating</a> 
          <br />
        
      </p>
      <br />
    
    <div><table style="width: 100%;" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="10">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td width="100%" bgcolor="#f88e20">
<table style="width: 100%; border: #ffffff 1px solid;" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="8">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td width="10%" valign="top"><img title="Balance Your Trailer Load" src="http://fileresource.sitepro.com/filemanager/169/imagecollections/1545/4601DB45-ED09-D71F-F0C5-5AB519F61E63.jpg" alt="Balance Your Trailer Load" width="140" height="187" /></td>
<td width="45%" valign="top"><span style="color: #ffffff;"><strong>In This Article, You Will Learn:</strong></span><br />
<div style="padding-left: 10px;"><span style="color: #ffffff;">&bull; Why&nbsp;Load Balance is &nbsp;Important</span></div>
<div style="padding-left: 10px;"><span style="color: #ffffff;">&bull; How Inches Matter</span></div>
<div style="padding-left: 10px;"><span style="color: #ffffff;">&bull; Tips for Backing Up</span></div>
</td>
<td width="45%" valign="top"><span style="color: #ffffff;"><strong>Glossary Terms Used in This Article:</strong></span><br />
<div style="padding-left: 10px;"><span style="color: #ffffff;">&bull; <a class="glossary" href="index.html#">Weight Distribution Hitch</a></span></div>
<div style="padding-left: 10px;"><span style="color: #ffffff;">&bull; <a class="glossary">Axle</a></span></div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><br /><em>Written by Jeff Zurschmeide<br style="font-style: italic;" /></em><br />Trailer manufacturers all talk about balancing the weight on (or in) a trailer for better handling, but from years of observation it looks like most people just pile stuff on and go. Most of the time this is OK because most loads aren't anywhere near the capacity of the trailer or tow vehicle. But especially as loads get heavier, getting the weight balanced correctly can make a big difference in handling. But what's more immediate for most people is that balancing your trailer's load has a big impact on your fuel economy.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>I recently loaned my 2000 Ford F250 Super Duty with 7.3-liter Powerstroke Diesel and my 8x20 Haulmark enclosed car hauler to a friend who needed to tow his race car about 400 miles. I explained that the trailer weighs about 3,000 pounds, and his car also weighs about 3,000 pounds. The trailer's capacity is 7,000 pounds and the truck will tow 10,000 pounds on its <a class="glossary" href="index.html#">weight distribution hitch</a>. So he was well within the practical limits.</p>
<p><img style="margin: 10px; vertical-align: middle;" title="WDH, Sway Control Device &amp; Spring Bars Diagram" src="http://fileresource.sitepro.com/filemanager/66/imagecollections/1956/E9FFC663-0C6A-77CC-214A-2DC9CBEC17C8.jpg" alt="WDH, Sway Control Device &amp; Spring Bars Diagram" width="500" height="229" />&nbsp;</p>
<p>I advised him to position the car in the center of the trailer, with the rear bumper as close to the rear entry door as he could get it without rubbing. That places the car's front wheels and engine just in front of the trailer's <a class="glossary" href="index.html#">axle</a>s, and delivers the 60% of load weight in front of the axles that is specified for most trailers. I explained that a difference of just a few inches would make a big difference in the way the rig felt on the road and the fuel economy he'd get on the trip.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>A few days later, he returned the truck and trailer (both washed, and the truck full of diesel - I like this guy!) and he told me that he learned I was right. He loaded the car with the rear bumper about 8 inches from the door, dead center in the trailer, and drove to his destination. He said the steering felt heavy and he could really feel the truck working to pull the trailer up hills. Consequently, he didn't get the fuel mileage I told him to expect. On the way home, he moved the car back until it was close to the door. "Then it felt like the trailer was hardly even there, and I got about 3 more miles to the gallon," he said.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The effect is more pronounced with a big heavy trailer, but the principle holds for all sizes. Don't overload the front of your trailer and pay attention to getting the right balance and you'll see results immediately in road-handling, and then again at the pump.</p>
<p><img style="margin: 10px;" src="http://fileresource.sitepro.com/filemanager/66/imagecollections/1956/84C1550A-5A02-FC6E-CF53-2A683B8FCAC4.jpg" alt="HitchInfo Logo" width="28" height="26" /></p></div>
